The paper deals with directed graph embedding and its application in Community Question Answering services (CQAs). The paper discusses the preservation of asymmetric transitivity in directed graphs, which is a characteristic property of such graphs. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of Information Retrieval (cs.IR), Machine Learning (cs.LG), Computational Linguistics (cs.CL), and Databases (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper also deals with routing and assigning newly posted questions to users with suitable expertise and interest in CQAs, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
